data.text:
This is a list of the oldest living people in the world. Supercentenarians that are categorised as "validated" have had their ages authenticated by an organisation that specialises in age validation, such as the European Supercentenarian Organisation (ESO)[1], Latin American Supercentenarians (LAS)[2], LongeviQuest (LQ)[3] Gerontology Research Group (GRG)[4], International Database on Longevity (IDL), or Guinness World Records (GWR).

Supercentenarians are categorised as "pending validation" if an organisation that specialises in age validation has some documentation to support their age, but their age has not yet been fully validated. Unverified supercentenarians listed below have not had their ages authenticated but there is sufficient reporting in reliable sources that provide a claimed date of birth. However, only claimants aged 110–114 that could potentially be validated in the future are included here.

As of 1 April 2022, the ESO[1] has validated 44 living supercentenarians; the LAS[2] has validated 17 living supercentenarians (and 18 are currently pending); and the GRG[4] has validated 15 living supercentenarians. In total, 70 living supercentenarians have had their age validated by an organisation that specialises in age validation (some being validated by multiple organisations).

Following the death of María Branyas Morera of Spain on 19 August 2024, Tomiko Itooka of Japan became the oldest living person whose age can be documented. She was born on 23 May 1908.

Bold names indicates the individual is believed to be the oldest resident of their country.
